    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the info. so if the ph is too high, it's like the iron is still there in the soil but the plant just can't grab it? it seems so weird that something can be right there and just be inaccessible. how does that work chemically?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's a great way to think about it. The iron in the soil is present, but it's not available to the plant because of the high pH. This is due to the way iron is chemically bound to the soil particles. \n\nWhen the soil pH is too high, the iron ions (Fe3+) are more likely to form insoluble compounds, such as iron oxides, which are not easily taken up by the plant. This is because the high pH causes the iron to bind to the soil particles more strongly, making it less available to the plant's roots.\n\nThink of it like a key and lock system. The iron ions are the keys, and the soil particles are the locks. When the pH is too high, the locks are too strong, and the keys can't fit, even if they're right there. This is why a lower pH, which makes the locks weaker, allows the keys to fit and the iron to be taken up by the plant.",
      "source": "target",
